        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>17 <sic>tober</sic> 54</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Enclosed please find<lb/> seven dollars 37 cts amount of 4
                (larger<lb/> size) prayer books sent less Express<lb/> charges as per a/c enclosed.
                I hope to<lb/> sell the small ones soon but would not<lb/> wait to remit you,
                although the books<lb/> are not yet paid for. I send by Express<lb/> because the
                post is not safe. I once<lb/> remitted to <persName>Moss &amp; Bro.</persName> In
                your city a small<lb/> amount which went where perhaps you<lb/> and <persName>Mr
                    Newhouses</persName> new <add>?</add> are. <persName>Mrs<lb/> Cohen</persName>
                sent a dollar in a letter to <persName>Sarah<lb/> Joseph</persName> a couple of
                weeks since, that also<lb/> has been <hi rend="underline">geganavd</hi><add>?</add>
                as a worthy Bar<lb/> Tismel here is accustomed to say. It will<lb/> cost you little
                more than post charges.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It trust you have by this<lb/> time received the copy of my
                father's<lb/> work on the “Melodies” which was ordered<lb/> to be sent you from
                    <placeName>New York</placeName>. The <placeName>London</placeName><lb/> press
                musical &amp; literary critics have<lb/> spoken in the highest terms of the
                books<lb/> and pronounced the melodies incomparably<lb/> solemn. Many of these
                melodies have</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>been introduced into the German synagogues<lb/> of <placeName>London</placeName>
                since the publication of<lb/> the book. I have yet received no<lb/> orders as to
                advertising it in the <placeName>U. S.</placeName><lb/> Jewish papers; but when you
                again<lb/> will, please let me what a square of<lb/> 10 or 12 lines will cost for
                one year.<lb/> I regret that only a few copies have<lb/> as yet arrived, and as many
                as I could<lb/> spare have gone to Editors—yours among<lb/> them sent from
                    <placeName>New York</placeName>; but I need<lb/> not add I shall be much pleased
                to<lb/> receive subscribers names from you<lb/> until you can be supplied; or if you<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">will send me the names I may be able</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">to send the books</hi>. The work has been<lb/> very successful
                indeed in <placeName>England</placeName>, and<lb/> as they possess the plates I hope
                that<lb/> if they meet with due encouragement<lb/> they will issue the book at a
                cheaper<lb/> rate, and also a volume of the chants<lb/> which are equally fine.
                Please bring<lb/> the book prominently before your reader<lb/> It deserves honorable
                mention.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Sarah Joseph</persName> desires me to<lb/> inform you that
                a copy of the Occident</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>is left for her regularly at <persName>Mrs Cohens</persName><lb/> in
                    <placeName>Philada</placeName>—so <persName>Mrs Cohen</persName> writes
                her.<lb/> Now as she receives one from me—you<lb/> yourself having directed it on
                some<lb/> occasions, there must be a mistake<lb/> here, which you will no doubt
                rectify.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">As far as I have been able to learn<lb/> I regret to say our few who
                buy prayer<lb/> books here are not likely to <add>?</add><lb/> the publication of
                the Hebrew Edition of prayers<lb/> you propose. If those who pay $10 for a<lb/> set
                of Hebrew are a class who would sooner<lb/> pay 8 more &amp; have a set of Hebrew
                &amp; English<lb/> —while those who buy all Hebrew prefer<lb/> those famous 5 dollar
                sets Feyertags<lb/> Gibethe den Sphaidim<add>?</add> published “Bey<lb/>
                <persName>Auton Edlen vore Sch<add>?</add></persName> (may his shadow<lb/> never be
                less—even if his paper &amp; print be<lb/> better.) This ever living house has
                issued<lb/> more than one sugar paper edition of<lb/> prayers with (such!) spanish
                or<lb/> rather Shponish. I once thought it<lb/> would do to print Hebrew daily
                prayers and<lb/> spoke to you about it. But <persName>Bush's</persName><lb/>
                <add>?</add>, and a very nice little one<lb/> printed in Amsterdam which Hazan<lb/>
                <persName>Lyons</persName>
                <sic>showd</sic> me when in <placeName>New York</placeName></p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>costing 25 cents put me out of <add>?</add><lb/> with such a notion.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">There is nothing stirring here<lb/> worth writing about. I hope
                your<lb/> synagogue gives a head and proves<lb/> that there is plenty of room
                for<lb/> two or even three for the Portuguese<lb/> Minhag in these days of
                Minhag<lb/> America</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I remain yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
